Mohamed Farah, 50, a  friend of the boy's family, said he called police more than once in October about a suspicious man who was coming around the center.

'I feel like I lost a part of my body,' he said after the teen's death.

Bakar Abdalla, 31, of Kansas City, said the boy's father was a teacher at the center. 

He said the man who had been frequenting the area with hateful messages was like a bullet in a gun waiting to be triggered.

Khadra Dirir, the victim's aunt, said her nephew regularly studied the Quran and had delivered a group prayer the night he died.

'If you asked him a verse, he could tell the chapter,' she said. 'I feel like I woke up in a bad dream.'

